ahman. \n\n=C2=A0\nFor example, con=\r\nsider a glass of water and an ocean. Both of them have the same \nchemical c=\r\nompostion (H2O). Realizing this is realizing &quot;all is Brahman&quot;. But an \nocea=\r\nn can sustain and create a Tsunami, a glass of water cannot, even if it \nwa=\r\nnts to. Of course it=C2=A0may often never have a desire to do so in the fir=\r\nst \nplace!=C2=A0However that is the difference, technically, between a gyan=\r\ni and a \nvi-gyani. And the whole process of a Siddha and higher starts ONLY=\r\n=C2=A0AFTER someone \nis able to bring the Kundalini back from Sahashra chak=\r\nra to the lower chakras \nagain. Needless to say, for most of us ordinary pe=\r\nople, even getting a Kundalini \nto awaken is a big deal, taking it to Shaha=\r\nshrar is already too hi fi and may \ntake lifetimes, bringing is back is imp=\r\nossible/unthinkable totally.\n=C2=A0\nWhat happens when a person becomes a Si=\r\nddha by the parameter described above? It \nis impossible to imagine. He/she=\r\n operates from a plane of reference so different \nthat ordinary folks just =\r\ncannot fathom. Infact, most of us can&#39;t even fathom \nwhat samadhi feels lik=\r\ne until experienced, what to speak of siddha-hood. \n\n=C2=A0\n_______________=\r\n___________________________\n=C2=A0\nA Trilanga Swami did tri-khanda yogas, c=\r\nuts his limbs, puts them=C2=A0into fire and \neventually the limbs regenerat=\r\ne. Even Sai Baba did a similar thing. Is this a \nsiddhi (miraculous ability=\r\n) or a sadhana? To us average folks, anything out of \nthe ordinary seems mi=\r\nraculous. The internet itself would appear \nsupernatural/miraculous a few c=\r\nenturies ago! \n\n=C2=A0\nTherefore, one who reaches a state of Siddha-hood, w=\r\nill automatically produce \nexternal effects which appear miraculous to ordi=\r\nnary people. Not like he/she \nis=C2=A0specifically trying for it, but it is=\r\n a byproduct of a totally different \ninternal=C2=A0reference frame. Hence t=\r\nhe crucial difference between a &quot;gyani&quot; and a \n&quot;vigyani&quot;. \n\n=C2=A0\nTo give =\r\nan example from physics, if you could move at speeds close to that of \nligh=\r\nt, you will see things elongating, time becoming slower, you will age less,=\r\n \netc etc.=C2=A0If you could move at speeds higher than that of light, you =\r\nwill observe \neffects of an action even before the action happens.=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0A supremely altered \nreference frame creates external effects which are =\r\nextraordinary and appear \nmiraculous to observers who are in a different re=\r\nference frame. This is the \nreality of the world. No amount of philosophy c=\r\nan change this.\n=C2=A0\n____________________________________________________=\r\n____\n=C2=A0\nEvery spiritual book has a point of view and an audience. Same =\r\nwith Aghora. One \nmay like=C2=A0it or one may not like it. But there is zer=\r\no scope of saying \nVimalananda knew something else=C2=A0and book creates a =\r\ndifferent impression etc etc. \nNothing=C2=A0of that sort. The chapter on Im=\r\nmortals in book 2 is very, very clear and \nvery direct. It is not possible =\r\nto interpret it any other way. \n\n=C2=A0\nOur scriptures have plenty of stori=\r\nes of miraculous things done by and \nassociated with Rishis. Did they have =\r\na desire from past lives? Which past life, \nwhen Rishis are eternal? The de=\r\nsire from past-life can explain why=C2=A0a sadhaka=C2=A0who \nhas not yet ex=\r\nperienced=C2=A0state of Brahman (nirvikalpa),=C2=A0striving for and \nattain=\r\ning xyz supernatural ability, but it cannot explain the \nexternal,=C2=A0mir=\r\naculous=C2=A0occurances which accompany a being who has attain \nsiddha-hood=\r\n or beyond (Rishis). To me, it is a natural byproduct of their vastly \ndiff=\r\nerent internal state of being. Not something they may have strived for, but=\r\n \nsomething that accompanies and manifests externally corresponding to thei=\r\nr \ninternal=C2=A0mastery over the=C2=A0elements.\n=C2=A0\n-Regards\n=C2=A0Raja=\r\nrshi\n\nBazeecha-e-atfal hain duniya mere aage.\nHota hain shab-o-roz tamasha =\r\nmere aage\n=C2=A0\nEk khel hain aurang-e-sulemaan mere nazdeek\nEk baat hain i=\r\njaz-e-masiah mere aage.\n\n\n\n\n________________________________\nFrom: Narasimh=\r\na PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt;\nTo: vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com\nSent: Thu, 4 A=\r\nugust, 2011 1:13:01 AM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] One more key point (Re: On S=\r\niddhis & Spiritual Progress)\n\n=C2=A0 \nNamaste,\n=C2=A0\nAn interesting point =\r\ncame up in a private exchange with a couple of folks and I \nwill write it d=\r\nown for the benefit of others.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nIt is not like =\r\n&quot;you get so & so siddhi when you reach so & so level&quot;.\n=C2=A0\nSiddhis come =\r\nbecause one DESIRED them in this or a PREVIOUS life. When one has \nmade eno=\r\nugh progress, Nature grants one&#39;s desires (or the ability to fulfil a \ngrou=\r\np of desires) and sees if that tempts one and one stops or one can progress=\r\n \nfurther.\n=C2=A0\nSo what siddhis one gets or does not get, is a function o=\r\nf (1) one&#39;s spiritual \nprogress now AND (2) all of one&#39;s desires until now =\r\n(in this life AND previous \nlives). At the same level of progress, two peop=\r\nle may fare differently in terms \nof what they get, based on what kind of w=\r\nishes they entertained in the past.\n=C2=A0\nSo siddhis cannot be used to mea=\r\nsure one&#39;s progress. You cannot use reverse of \nf(x, y) to gauge x, without=\r\n knowing y.\n=C2=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------------------------------=\r\n-----------------------------------\n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyot=\r\nish Lessons, Jyotish Writings,\n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short Ho=\r\nmam and Pitri Tarpana:\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A