l of existence and sadha=\r\nna is self-realization. Siddhis are to be neither \nspecifically sought nor =\r\nspecifically avoided, by a seeker of Self. If Nature \ngives one some siddhi=\r\n(s), one should accept them with neither excitement nor \ndisappointment. Bu=\r\nt one should NOT run after them, for they are neither \nnecessary nor suffic=\r\nient for self-realization and liberation. \n\n=C2=A0 \nVivekananda used the sa=\r\nme principle when Ramakirishna proposed to give his \nsiddhis to Vivekananda=\r\n. He asked whether the siddhis will enable him to realize \ngod. Ramakrishna=\r\n said no. Vivekananda firmly declined the offer then! Of course, \nwhen Rama=\r\nkrishna gave them anyway later, he accepted them. Vivekananda&#39;s two \naction=\r\ns demonstrate Vasishtha&#39;s instructions well. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=\r\n=A0 \nLet us use the analogy of climbing a hill. Climbing hill is one&#39;s spir=\r\nitual \nsadhana. Reaching the top is liberation. Different people climb the =\r\nhill from \ndifferent sides and using different paths. There may be trees wi=\r\nth nice fruits \non the sides of the road. They are siddhis or special abili=\r\nties. \n\n=C2=A0 \nIf one gets distracted, starts climbing the trees and colle=\r\ncting fruits, one&#39;s \njourney gets delayed and one may not reach the top. Th=\r\nat is why Vasishtha says a \nseeker of Self does not pursue any siddhis. \n\n=\r\n=C2=A0 \nBut if some fruits fall in one&#39;s lap by themselves, one can keep th=\r\nem. \nSimilarly, siddhis that come to one by themselves can be accepted by a=\r\n seeker of \nSelf. \n\n=C2=A0 \nNow an important distinction: \n=C2=A0 \nThere ar=\r\ne some trees that are found at lower altitudes also, but some really \nspeci=\r\nal trees are found at very high altitudes only. If one has such a fruit, it=\r\n \nshows that one has climbed great heights. Similarly, some siddhis do not =\r\nmean \nmuch, but some siddhis are very special and only really elevated sadh=\r\nakas can \nobtain them (whether by trying or without trying). If a sadhakas =\r\ndemonstrates \nsuch a siddhi, you can see that one progressed a lot. However=\r\n, the key is that \none who climbed the same or more distance may not have t=\r\nhat or any other fruit. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nUnlike in the ex=\r\nample of climbing hill, which is an external activity, spiritual \nprogress =\r\nin real life is *internal*. There is NO way for anyone to know for sure \nho=\r\nw much progress one has made, how much self-control one has internally and =\r\n\nwhat exactly goes on in one&#39;s mind. We may try to judge it from external f=\r\nactors \nsuch as actions, words etc, but it is not necessarily accurate. \n\n=\r\n=C2=A0 \nHere, some people swayed by siddhis may be tempted to use one&#39;s sid=\r\ndhis to judge \nhow high one climbed. But that is faulty. One person who rea=\r\nched the absolute \ntop may not have any fruits, while one person who still =\r\nhas ways to climb may \nhave gotten some really nice fruit. Using externasll=\r\ny demonstrable siddhis that \nare neither necessary nor sufficient for Self-=\r\nrealization as a measure of one&#39;s \nprogress is unsound. \n\n=C2=A0 \nGiven tha=\r\nt spiritual progress is internal, how can we judge it and compare \npeople t=\r\nhen? Well, we need not and should not. Only a sarvaantaryaami - a \nperfecte=\r\nd being who has access to each being&#39;s internal state - can do that. \n\n=C2=\r\n=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nRajarshi, you are assuming that Ramakrishna P=\r\naramahamsa is a Paramahamsa on \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. You are concluding tha=\r\nt Ramakrishna is a Paramahamsa; \nAbhedananda, Vivekananda etc are lower tha=\r\nn that; Vimalananda is a rishi; and \nhence Vimalananda is superior to Abhed=\r\nananda and Vivekananda by 2pwr16 to 2. \n\n=C2=A0 \nIs Paramahamsa Nithyananda=\r\n, who was caught in a sex scandal, also a Paramahamsa \nbecause he is known =\r\nso? See, how people are famously known may or may not \nreflect their spirit=\r\nual stature. Real spiritual stature is internal and you \ncannot see it. \n\n=\r\n=C2=A0 \nWe do not know who Ramakrishna Paramahamsa really is. He may not be=\r\n just a \nparamahamsa on Vimalananda&#39;s scale, but be a siddha or a natha or =\r\neven a rishi. \nHe may even be Vishnu himself, as he himself said and some r=\r\neligious experts of \nthat time declared based on various signs. If Ramakris=\r\nhna Paramahamsa is Vishnu \nhimself, Vivekananda, Abhedananda etc can defini=\r\ntely be rishis or naths in \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. If your argument is that t=\r\nhey cannot be because they did \nnot demonstrate siddhis compatible with tha=\r\nt status, that is a non-point as I \nexplained above. The disagreement betwe=\r\nen then boils down a difference in the \nrelevance and importance of externa=\r\nlly demonstrated siddhis. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nWhy this is r=\r\nelevant and I spent some time on this is that some people seem to \nhave mis=\r\nconceptions. The take home for some people from some books describing \nmira=\r\ncles and siddhis may be that siddhis are important. \n\n=C2=A0 \nVasishtha is =\r\nnot only a rishi, but one of saptarshis. Please read what he taught \nLord R=\r\nama in Yoga Vaasishtham. It is the essence of Veda and Upanishad. It will \n=\r\nbalance your views and mould your attitude. Read Yoga Vaasishtham. Siddhis =\r\nare \nneither necessary nor sufficient for self-realization. Don&#39;t be distra=\r\ncted by \nthem or be infatuated with them. \n\n=C2=A0 \nThe goal of sadhana is =\r\nthat your notions of &quot;this is I and these are mine&quot; get \nsubtler and subtle=\r\nr and hold of six internal enemies on you becomes weaker and \nweaker. Other=\r\ns may or may not be able to see and judge your progress, but you \nknow your=\r\n progress and weaknesses the best. THAT is the crux and siddhis have no \nre=\r\nlevance or meaning. Any fascination for them will set you back in your \nsad=\r\nhana. \n\n=C2=A0 \nBest regards, \nNarasimha \n---------------------------------=\r\n---------------------------------- \n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyot=\r\nish Lessons, Jyotish Writings, \n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short H=\r\nomam and Pitri Tarpana: \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 http://www.VedicAstr=\r\nologer.org \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Films that make a difference: http://S=\r\naraswatiFilms.org \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Spirituality: http://groups.yah=\r\noo.com/group/vedic-wisdom \n=C2=A0 Jyotish writings: http://groups.yahoo.com=\r\n/group/JyotishWritings \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Twitt=\r\ner ID: @homam108 \n---------------------------------------------------------=\r\n---------- \n=C2=A0 \n--- In vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com, Narasimha PVR Rao =\r\n&lt;pvr@...&gt; wrote: \n&gt; \n&gt; Namaste friends, \n&gt; \n&gt; There was a long friendly ;-)=\r\n exchange between Rajarshi and me on Friday \n&gt; (July 29) on twitter on meas=\r\nuring spiritual caliber. This came from the \n&gt; context of Rajarshi&#39;s commen=\r\nts on the &quot;maturity&quot; & &quot;errors&quot; of \n&gt; Ramakrishna&#39;s disciples (regarding th=\r\neir attitude towards Tantra). He \n&gt; compared them with Vimalananda and said=\r\n their spiritual caliber was of \n&gt; the scale of 2, while Vimalananda&#39;s was =\r\n2 power 16. He also talked about \n&gt; the hierarchy of spiritual caliber ment=\r\nioned by V. I want to share 2 \n&gt; cents of musings on that. \n&gt; \n&gt; ----------=\r\n--------------------- \n&gt; Measuring Spiritual Caliber \n&gt; \n&gt; Rajarshi, here a=\r\nre a few comments on your statements a couple of days \n&gt; back on Twitter co=\r\nmparing spiritual caliber. We can&#39;t even compare \n&gt; flowers like hibiscus, =\r\nrose, jasmine, mogra, kewda, lotus etc & say \n&gt; which is a better flower. T=\r\nhey have different properties like color, \n&gt; size, shape, number of petals,=\r\n type/intensity of smell etc. Relative \n&gt; values depend on the purpose and =\r\nthey cannot be quantified universally. \n&gt; How can any sane person then say =\r\nthat spiritual caliber of different \n&gt; people can be compared and quanitifi=\r\ned? The field of duality has \n&gt; infinite variety and the [self-]control of =\r\na yogi has infinite aspects \n&gt; to it. You cannot quantify the spiritual cal=\r\niber of a person as one \n&gt; number and compare them. \n&gt; \n&gt; Before one even a=\r\nttempts to understand Vimalananda&#39;s order (Paramahamsa \n&gt; &lt; Siddha &lt; Natha =\r\n&lt; Rishi), please note that different hierarchies exist \n&gt; in scriptures for=\r\n deities also. Some consider a hierarchy of deities \n&gt; where Vishnu is supr=\r\neme. Some consider a hierarchy of deities where \n&gt; Shiva is supreme. Some c=\r\nonsider a hierarchy of deities where Shakti is \n&gt; supreme. And so on. None =\r\nof them is absolute. All of them are relative \n&gt; and for specific purposes,=\r\n i.e. from a specific perspective. There are \n&gt; people who take them as abs=\r\nolute and argue that so and so thing taught \n&gt; by Vishnu is superior to so =\r\nand so thing taught by Shiva, etc. But we \n&gt; know that none of the hierarch=\r\nies is absolute. \n&gt; \n&gt; One who has the nerve to think that one can compare =\r\nthe wisdom of \n&gt; Jnaneshwar, dispassion of Ramana Maharshi, mad devotion of=\r\n Ramakrishna \n&gt; Paramahamsa, detached activism of Vivekananda, compassion o=\r\nf Shirdi Sai, \n&gt; spiritual ecstasy of Vama Khepa, inner clarity of Lahiri M=\r\nahashaya, \n&gt; detachment of Trilinga Swami, purity of Tukaram, humility of E=\r\nknath \n&gt; Maharaj, ecstatic love of Meera Bai, motherly love of Gopaler Ma, =\r\netc, \n&gt; is a fool of the highest order. They can be compared from specific =\r\n\n&gt; limited perspectives. In one thing, Tukaram may be superior to all, in \n=\r\n&gt; another Jnaneshwar, in another Trilinga, in another Ramakrishna, and so \n=\r\n&gt; on. You cannot compare in absolute terms. You should not even try to. \n&gt; =\r\nYou should just appreciate them individually and aspire to be like any \n&gt; o=\r\nf them that you like the most. \n&gt; \n&gt; Vimalananda&#39;s list may be correct from=\r\n specific perspective. More \n&gt; importantly, his words should make one reali=\r\nze that there is always \n&gt; scope for further self-control (and the resultin=\r\ng mastery over the field \n&gt; of duality) while one is still embodied. One sh=\r\nould never rest and \n&gt; aspire for better self-control. But taking it as gos=\r\npel and starting to \n&gt; judge yogis based on that is unwise. Especially maki=\r\nng statements like \n&gt; &quot;Vimalananda is heavier than all RK&#39;s discples put to=\r\ngtr&quot; and thinking \n&gt; that something is absolute truth because Vimalananda i=\r\ns assumed to have \n&gt; said that (vs someone &quot;lower than him&quot;) is unwise. \n&gt; =\r\n\n&gt; Even if Vimalananda&#39;s hierarchy is absolute and universal, don&#39;t assume =\r\n\n&gt; that you can judge the stature of each yogi accurately. Because \n&gt; Ramak=\r\nrishna was popularly known as a Paramahamsa, is he a Paramahamsa as \n&gt; per =\r\nVimalananda&#39;s classification or a siddha or a natha or even a rishi? \n&gt; Or =\r\nmay be a deity? My friend, don&#39;t assume you know for sure!!! Based on \n&gt; th=\r\ne details we know, can we be absolutely sure of even Vimalananda&#39;s \n&gt; statu=\r\nre based on his own classification? \n&gt; \n&gt; You said &quot;Approximating 2 equal t=\r\no each disciples of ramakrishna. 2exp16 \n&gt; =3D say Vimalananda. Basic?&quot; You=\r\n probably made this statement based on \n&gt; what you read and heard of Vimala=\r\nnanda. For the sake of argument, it is \n&gt; not even 100% clear whether he wa=\r\ns a real person or an imagined \n&gt; character. Svoboda intentionally (and ver=\r\ny wisely!) left the latter \n&gt; option open in the preface of his Aghora book=\r\n! \n&gt; \n&gt; If we MUST compare spiritual calibers, one possibility is to use a =\r\n\n&gt; simpler definition of how close one is to liberation as a measure of \n&gt; =\r\none&#39;s &quot;spiritual caliber&quot;, Ramakrishna&#39;s disciples fare quite well. RK \n&gt; t=\r\nold Abhedananda that it was going to be his last birth. Others would be \n&gt; =\r\nback, but he would be liberated. To Yogananda, he said there would be \n&gt; on=\r\ne more birth and he would be free forever after that. Vimalananda, on \n&gt; th=\r\ne other hand, had atleast one more birth clearly as he said a body was \n&gt; w=\r\naiting for him. That way, forget about &quot;RK&#39;s discples put togtr&quot;, just \n&gt; A=\r\nbhedananda alone is superior to Vimalananda! \n&gt; \n&gt; Again, please note that =\r\nthis is just one definition. One can have many \n&gt; definitions. The key is n=\r\not to jump to unwise conclusions on any \n&gt; hierarchies and say that &quot;X is w=\r\neightier than Y and so what he said must \n&gt; be more correct&quot;. \n&gt; \n&gt; People =\r\nwith lopsided understanding of scriptures take relative knowledge \n&gt; to be =\r\nabsolute and jump to unwise conclusions. I am afraid some people \n&gt; are doi=\r\nng the same now with &quot;modern scriptures&quot; such as the Aghora \n&gt; books. Don&#39;t=\r\n fall into the trap of taking something as gospel or as \n&gt; absolute. Writte=\r\nn words are always relative and never absolute. \n&gt; Discriminate relative kn=\r\nowledge using intellect at first and hopefully \n&gt; using experencial realiza=\r\ntion later on. \n&gt; \n&gt; More importantly, while we are still searching for &quot;ma=\r\nturity&quot;, we should \n&gt; not commit the &quot;error&quot; of making negative judgmental =\r\ncomments of greats \n&gt; who did far more sadhana than us and experienced a lo=\r\nt more than us. \n&gt; ------------------------------- \n&gt; \n&gt; Best regards, \n&gt; N=\r\narasimha \n\r\n--0-876920484-1312455002=:81096\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;style type=3D&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- DIV {margin:0px;} --&gt;&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/he=\r\nad&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;font-family:times new roman, new york, times, serif;=\r\nfont-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;Namaste,&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;Some=\r\n thoughts on Siddhas.&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;&lt;&lt;FONT color=3D#0=\r\n00000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;It is not like &quot;you get so &amp; so siddhi wh=\r\nen you reach so &amp; so level&quot;.&gt;&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dle=\r\nft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FON=\r\nT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;Before we go further, let us define what is&nbsp;=\r\n&quot;siddhi&quot; and what is a&nbsp;&quot;siddha&quot;. Siddhi means accomplishment. That is =\r\nwhy we used terms like mantra-siddhi (realizing a mantra), or some other ap=\r\nparently miraculous/supernatural ability.&nbsp;And the word siddha is&nbsp;=\r\noften used&nbsp;to describe someone who has some such ability.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;=\r\n\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV a=\r\nlign=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;This definition of a Siddha is in=\r\ncorrect. It is a corruption which has entered our thought-process over cent=\r\nuries, just like every other spiritual person who uses an epithet Rishi is =\r\nnot really a Rishi.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVe=\r\nrdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;S=\r\no who is a Siddha really? One who has acquired some miraculous ability? Nop=\r\ne. Technically a Siddha is one who has taken his awareness (Kundalini) to t=\r\nhe Sahashrar Chakra, thus experiencing Nirvikalpa, and THEN bringing the aw=\r\nareness back to the lower chakras. In this process, he often acquires *degr=\r\nees of mastery* over the five elements of the chakras. That is a true Siddh=\r\na.&nbsp;Aghora part 2 very clearly defines, (same is also hinted at in some=\r\n other books too), this in much details. There is absolutely no scope of am=\r\nbiguity here, unless one refuses to accept the book as valid (fine by me).&=\r\nnbsp;Like it says, what is the difference between a gyani and a vigyani? A =\r\ngyani experiences the state of Nirvikalpa and realizes &quot;All is Brahman&quot;. Bu=\r\nt it is one thing to realize &quot;all is brahman&quot;, it is another thing to acqui=\r\nre some of the shaktis of Brahman. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT si=\r\nze=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 =\r\nface=3DVerdana&gt;F&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;or example, consider a=\r\n glass of water and an ocean. Both of them have the same chemical compostio=\r\nn (H2O). Realizing this is realizing &quot;all is Brahman&quot;. But an ocean can sus=\r\ntain and create a Tsunami, a glass of water cannot, even if it wants to. Of=\r\n course it&nbsp;may often never have a desire to do so in the first place!&=\r\nnbsp;However that is the difference, technically, between a gyani and a vi-=\r\ngyani. And the whole process of a Siddha and higher starts ONLY&nbsp;AFTER =\r\nsomeone is able to bring the Kundalini back from Sahashra chakra to the low=\r\ner chakras again. Needless to say, for most of us ordinary people, even get=\r\nting a Kundalini to awaken is a big deal, taking it to Shahashrar is alread=\r\ny too hi fi and may take lifetimes, bringing is back is impossible/unthinka=\r\nble totally.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;=\r\n/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;What hap=\r\npens when a person becomes a Siddha by the parameter described above? It is=\r\n impossible to imagine. He/she operates from a plane of reference so differ=\r\nent that ordinary folks just cannot fathom. Infact, most of us can&#39;t even f=\r\nathom what samadhi feels like until experienced, what to speak of siddha-ho=\r\nod. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&n=\r\nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;________________=\r\n__________________________&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 fa=\r\nce=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVe=\r\nrdana&gt;A Trilanga Swami did tri-khanda yogas, cuts his limbs, puts them&nbsp=\r\n;into fire and eventually the limbs regenerate. Even Sai Baba did a similar=\r\n thing. Is this a siddhi (miraculous ability) or a sadhana? To us average f=\r\nolks, anything out of the ordinary seems miraculous. The internet itself wo=\r\nuld appear supernatural/miraculous a few centuries ago! &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV =\r\nalign=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=\r\n=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;Therefore, one who reaches a state of=\r\n Siddha-hood, will automatically produce external effects which appear mira=\r\nculous to ordinary people. Not like he/she is&nbsp;specifically trying for =\r\nit, but it is a byproduct of a totally different internal&nbsp;reference fr=\r\name. Hence the crucial difference between a &quot;gyani&quot; and a &quot;vigyani&quot;. &lt;/FONT=\r\n&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;=\r\n\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;To give an example from ph=\r\nysics, if you could move at speeds close to that of light, you will see thi=\r\nngs elongating, time becoming slower, you will age less, etc etc.&nbsp;If y=\r\nou could move at speeds higher than that of light, you will observe effects=\r\n of an action even before the action happens.&nbsp;&nbsp;A supremely altere=\r\nd reference frame creates external effects which are extraordinary and appe=\r\nar miraculous to observers who are in a different reference frame. This is =\r\nthe reality of the world. No amount of philosophy can change this.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/=\r\nDIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;D=\r\nIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;_____________________________=\r\n___________________________&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 f=\r\nace=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DV=\r\nerdana&gt;Every spiritual book has a point of view and an audience. Same with =\r\nAghora. One may like&nbsp;it or one may not like it. But there is zero scop=\r\ne of saying Vimalananda knew something else&nbsp;and book creates a differe=\r\nnt impression etc etc. Nothing&nbsp;of that sort. The chapter on Immortals =\r\nin book 2 is very, very clear and very direct. It is not possible to interp=\r\nret it any other way. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=\r\n=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerd=\r\nana&gt;Our scriptures have plenty of stories of miraculous things done by and =\r\nassociated with Rishis. Did they have a desire from past lives? Which past =\r\nlife, when Rishis are eternal? The desire from past-life can explain why&nb=\r\nsp;a sadhaka&nbsp;who has not yet experienced&nbsp;state of Brahman (nirvik=\r\nalpa),&nbsp;striving for and attaining xyz supernatural ability, but it can=\r\nnot explain the external,&nbsp;miraculous&nbsp;occurances which accompany a=\r\n being who has attain siddha-hood or beyond (Rishis). To me, it is a natura=\r\nl byproduct of their vastly different internal state of being. Not somethin=\r\ng they may have strived for, but something that accompanies and manifests e=\r\nxternally corresponding to their internal&nbsp;mastery over the&nbsp;elemen=\r\nts.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nb=\r\nsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;-Regards&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/=\r\nDIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp;Rajarshi&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;=\r\n/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;EM&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;\n&lt;DIV class=3DM=\r\nsoNormal&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;SPAN style=3D&quot;FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; COLOR: navy; FONT-SIZ=\r\nE: 10pt&quot;&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 face=3D&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;SPAN styl=\r\ne=3D&quot;COLOR: #000066&quot; class=3DApple-style-span&gt;&lt;SPAN style=3D&quot;FONT-SIZE: med=\r\nium&quot; class=3DApple-style-span&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#a2a2a2 size=3D3&gt;Bazeecha-e-atf=\r\nal hain duniya mere aage.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;SPAN styl=\r\ne=3D&quot;COLOR: #000066&quot; class=3DApple-style-span&gt;&lt;SPAN style=3D&qu